postcontent: Springfield Armory M1A Loaded mounted in a Blackfeather stock. This stock is similar to the Sage EBR in that it uses a op rod guide that is mated to the stock to make the rifle more accurate. The Blackfeather uses a tension adjustable op rod guide to fine tune the accuracy. It is also about 2 lbs lighter that the Sage EBR and includes three adjustable rails.You can read all the specifics on the stock at the web site: www.m14.ca/m14m1a-blackfeather-rs.htmlThe rifle has Smith Enterprises trigger parts and a trigger shoe. Pulling the trigger straight back is needed for accuracy when using a stock with a grip.It has a national match barrel, front sight, and a Sadlak NM spring guide. The muzzle device is the CA legal. The stock is a MAKO Fab Defense and the cheek riser adjustable and very solid.The bipod is a Atlas clone but is a really close match and very stable.The sight mount is Basset Machine, bassetmachine.com and a riser to clear the optic. The optic is a Burris Fullfield 4-20x50 and it is supposed to be OD green but I think they missed it. title: For Sale:  Police Package of S&W 10-5 revolver, Jay-Pee holster, Bianchi belt, extra grips
postcontent: As I near the end of the sell off of my guns, this is a unique opportunity to own the gun, holster, and belt used by a police officer in New Jersey. This police package came from an estate sale.The revolver is a 1968 model Smith & Wesson Model blued 10-5 that shows "character" and wears it with pride! This was the everyday carry weapon for this police officer until his retirement many years ago. Bore and cylinder are clean and everything feels tight. The rear sights and front ramp have white paint lightly dabbed on for the "old school" edition of fiber optic sights we have today.The revolver has lots of holster wear and some light freckling in a few spots, but I think it is in better aesthetic condition than I would have expected from a career long everyday use and carry gun. This gun has not been abused, as this is just honest wear from being on the job for many years. There is wear primarily on the inside corners where they rubbed while in the holster, but there is also much evidence externally of it being a true "on the job" weapon. Bore and chambers on the cylinder are good and have been well maintained. After all, this officer's life depended on this gun working every time he might have to pull the trigger.The gun came to me with beautiful custom-made dark walnut with target thumb rest grips. I will include them in the sale, but the buyer has their choice of an additional pair of either Smith & Wesson wood grips or rubber Pachmayr Gripper grips. I have attached pics of the gun with the original target grips, as well as pics of both options to help you decide which of the two bonus options you prefer.I had the gun's side plate off and completely cleaned while intact the internals, then oiled them before replacing the side plate. That helped improve an already smooth trigger and added to the accuracy of the gun.The holster is a Jay-Pee Spring Lock Safety Swivel Holster that features a trigger guard click retention button to keep the pistol securely inside the holster until it can easily be removed with a push of the finger as you draw the pistol. It also has space on the belt to hold a dozen .38 Special bullets. The belt is a Bianchi 42 with adjustable sizing and quick connection prongs.This is a really cool police package that will easily take you back in time to when this officer carried his gun with this belt and holster.Local face-to-face cash sale only. Buyer must be at least 21, Oklahoma resident able to legally buy a firearm in Oklahoma, and must have a current valid Oklahoma issued picture ID. No exceptions.$275 for the entire package. Please contact me if you would like to see the belt and holster pic and other pictures I have available.

title: For Sale:  1962 Winchester Model 100
postcontent: This is a 1962 Winchester Model 100.  This is confirmed by the serial number.  I am the 2nd owner, the original owner purchased it new in '62.  The Winchester model 100 was a departure for Winchester, semi auto box magazine, this one chambered in .308.  I have two magazines.  The sling mounts are factory, all model 100s had sling mounts.  The bottom of the barrel towards the muzzle has just a few tiny specks of surface rust but it wouldn't show up well for the camera.  The only places the bluing has been rubbed off a bit are just forward of the scope on the top of the barrel, but overall the bluing is very nice, the receiver looks new really.   Overall, 80-90%, and I would have went higher if not for those two spots.  The stock has a couple of scratches here and there, but no huge gouges.  The bore is good with good rifling as you can see.  The model 100 had a firing pin recall in the early 90s, I called Winchester and confirmed this gun had not had the work done (the original owner probably ran two boxes of 20 rounds through this gun total) and they sent firing pin to me and I installed it myself.  The scope and mounts are the parts installed in the 60s, Weaver pivot mounts (scope flips to the side for use of iron sights).  I have shot this gun after the firing pin change, it works as it should and worked flawlessly.  If you are a pre-64 Winchester collector, here's one you probably don't have...apparently I can only upload 3 pics, so if interested let me know and I will send more. No scams, no morons, I am very blunt and won't deal with stupidity.
